  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is your advice for a 25 year old guy who is broken and see no hope in his future?",
  "response": "I'm really sorry that you're feeling this way. Here are some steps and pieces of advice that may help you navigate this difficult period:\n\n1. **Reach Out for Support**: Don\u2019t hesitate to seek help from friends, family, or a professional counselor or therapist. Sharing your feelings with someone trustworthy can provide relief and perspective.\n\n2. **Reflect and Identify the Cause**: Take some time to understand what specifically is making you feel broken and hopeless. Identifying the root cause can help you develop a plan to address it.\n\n3. **Set Small, Achievable Goals**: Sometimes large goals can feel overwhelming. Start by setting small, manageable goals that can provide a sense of accomplishment and gradually build confidence.\n\n4. **Focus on Self-Care**: Pay attention to your physical health. Regular exercise, a balanced diet, adequate sleep, and relaxation techniques like meditation or deep breathing can boost your mood.\n\n5. **Avoid Negative Coping Mechanisms**: Resist the temptation to turn to substance abuse or other harmful behaviors to escape your feelings. These can make things worse in the long run.\n\n6. **Develop a Routine**: Having a consistent daily routine can provide structure and a sense of normalcy, which can be comforting during distressing times.\n\n7. **Engage in Activities You Enjoy**: Spend time doing things that you enjoy or used to enjoy. Hobbies and interests can be a great way to distract yourself and find moments of joy.\n\n8. **Consider Professional Help**: If your feelings persist, it may be beneficial to consult a mental health professional who can provide therapy or medication to help manage your symptoms.\n\n9. **Practice Gratitude**: Sometimes shifting focus to what you do have rather than what you don\u2019t can alter your perspective. Make a habit of noting things you are grateful for each day.\n\n10. **Volunteer or Help Others**: Helping others can often provide a sense of purpose and improve your own mood. Volunteering can be a great way to meet new people and distract yourself from personal struggles.\n\n11. **Take Things One Day at a Time**: It can be overwhelming to think too far into the future. Try to focus on getting through each day, and gradually you may find things improving.\n\nRemember, it\u2019s okay to feel this way, and it\u2019s okay to seek help. You\u2019re not alone, and things can get better.",
